caption: A small plaque identifying the building where Marie Curie lived from 1912 to 1934 (and where René Cassin later lived as well). Very cool to pass by! No entry into the actual building.
There's a small information plate on the wall. You can't get in. Just ordinary house. But it was nice to imagine old times, and Marie Curie walked around the block. Beautiful area.
If you know who she is and you like off the main touristy path and are on the island then this is a easy spot to walk by for a photo opportunity.
You can't actually visit the house of Marie Curie.

It is very nice to be able to go to the place of residence of this brilliant person (like a place of pilgrimage of sorts). Everything is done in simplicity so as not to transform the building into a memorial, a humble plaque indicates the building where Marie Curie lived.
Great Lady: an exceptional scientist, the first woman to win the Nobel Prize and the only one to have received TWO! A Nobel family and this view of Notre Dame during the journey
Mrs. Curie, everyone should know this!
I could have visitors at the house. But it's cool to know that she lived there!
Small museum about the life and work of Marie Curie and co......but very fascinating for enthusiasts!!
